* Micron periodically audits contractor's performance through Micron's existing EHSS auditing processes.  A minimum of one PSM/RMP contractor audit will be performed per year; and

* Contractor injury and illnesses associated with work on or near the covered PSM process will be maintained in a log.  All injuries and illnesses records are maintained in the company SAP database.  For investigation tracking purposes a SharePoint site has been established (alias ICAT - restricted access) to track investigation closure and causal factors.  Events associated with the PSM/RMP covered process will be indicated by the Safety investigator as such, creating a sortable log to distinguish between those related to the covered process. 



Micron's contract partners are expected to do the following:



* Assure contractor employees are trained in applicable work practices;

* Assure contractor is instructed in the hazards related to their job and the process;

* Document that training was delivered and understood;

* Ensure contractors follow the safety rules of the facility; and

* Advise Micron of any unique hazards presented by contract employer's work.



Micron has communicated expectations in writing to those contracting companies advising them of their responsibilities associated with potential work on or around the covered process as part of the contractor evaluation process.



FIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY:

The system is new as of the initial filing of the PSM/RMP documents.  There is no accident history associated with this PSM/RMP covered process.



In the event that an accidental release from the covered process occurs resulting in deaths, injuries, or signific

ant property damage on-site, or known off-site deaths, injuries, evacuations, sheltering in place, property damage, or environmental damage, Micron will record and report the following within 6-months of the event: 



* Date, time, and approximate duration of the release; 

* Chemical released; 

* Estimated quantity released in pounds; 

* NAICS code; 

* The type of release event and its source; 

* Weather conditions (if known); 

* On-site impacts; 

* Known off-site impacts; 

* Initiating event and contributing factors (if known); 

* Whether off-site responders were notified (if known); and 

* Operational or process changes that resulted from investigation of the release and that have been made by the time this information is submitted in accordance with Part 68.168. 



EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM:

Micron has emergency response procedures at the Boise site that include emergency notification, evacuation procedures and emergency response to compressed gas leaks. Micron personnel will respond to accidental releases of ammonia. The Boise Micron site is included and participates with Ada City-County Emergency Management, the local emergency planning committee (LEPC). In addition to Micron's existing emergency response team (ERT) system, Micron has completed the following activities applicable to the bulk ammonia distribution system:



* Received training from the supplier (Air Products) around ERT response methods, hazards and conditions to avoid associated with potential leaks at the ammonia ISO container pad (Air Products ERT Training);

* Conducted training and orientation with the local Fire Department;

* Developed specific response procedures for response to a potential release from the bulk ammonia distribution system; and

* Trained ERT technician level employees on specific response procedures associated with emergency shutdown and containment, evacuation and PPE.



